When running the application, you need to make sure your current working directory is set correctly so Python can find the module.

Here are a few ways to fix this:

1. Run the application from the `backend` directory:

<augment_code_snippet mode="EDIT">
```bash
# Navigate to the backend directory first
cd backend
# Then run the application
python -m app.main
```
</augment_code_snippet>

2. Or use the absolute import path when running from the project root:

<augment_code_snippet mode="EDIT">
```bash
# From the project root
python -m backend.app.main
```
</augment_code_snippet>

3. Alternatively, you can add the backend directory to your Python path:

<augment_code_snippet mode="EDIT">
```bash
# Set PYTHONPATH environment variable
export PYTHONPATH=$PYTHONPATH:/path/to/your/backend
# Then run
python -m app.main
```
</augment_code_snippet>

The most common solution is option 1 - simply navigate to the backend directory before running the application.
